<!-- ═══ FRAMEWORK ═══ -->
<section id="framework">
  <h2>What Students Learn — Six Skill Areas</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">Every SLE lesson develops six interconnected skill areas that together build real communicative ability. The first five are the classic dimensions of language competence. The sixth — Communication Strategies — is what keeps learners talking when their language isn't enough yet.</p>

  <div class="comp-grid">
    <div class="comp-card c-vocab"><div class="num">Skill 1</div><h4>Vocabulary</h4><p>The words and phrases learners need, organized by real-life situations — not random lists. Each level builds a new set of high-frequency terms anchored in Mexican cultural contexts.</p></div>
    <div class="comp-card c-grammar"><div class="num">Skill 2</div><h4>Grammar & Verb Patterns</h4><p>How sentences work — from basic present tense to subjunctive and conditional. Includes verb combinations like <em>ir a + infinitive</em> and <em>tener que + infinitive</em> that express intention, obligation, and possibility.</p></div>
    <div class="comp-card c-connectors"><div class="num">Skill 3</div><h4>Connectors & Text Organization</h4><p>The words that hold ideas together — from simple sequencing (<em>primero, después</em>) to argumentative structure (<em>sin embargo, por lo tanto</em>). Without connectors, sentences are islands.</p></div>
    <div class="comp-card c-pronunciation"><div class="num">Skill 4</div><h4>Pronunciation & Writing</h4><p>How Spanish sounds and how it's written. Covers the vowel system, accent marks as grammar markers, spelling changes in verb forms, and intonation patterns that carry meaning.</p></div>
    <div class="comp-card c-context"><div class="num">Skill 5</div><h4>Context, Culture & Appropriateness</h4><p>Knowing <em>what</em> to say is grammar. Knowing <em>how</em> to say it is this. Covers register (tú/usted), courtesy, cultural norms, and the Mexican indirectness that shapes real conversations.</p></div>
    <div class="comp-card c-strategies"><div class="num">Skill 6</div><h4>Communication Strategies</h4><p>What to do when you don't have the right word — repair, circumlocution, hedging, self-correction, and text editing. The skill that keeps communication alive while the others catch up.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ SP101 ═══ -->
<section id="sp101">
  <div class="level-header sp101">
    <h2>SP101 — Elementary Spanish I</h2>
    <div class="target">ACTFL Target: Novice Mid/High</div>
    <div class="desc">Building the self and the immediate present. Learners manage everyday interactions, describe their world, and express simple intentions — all in present tense, with formulaic language and high-frequency vocabulary.</div>
  </div>

  <h3>SP101 — Full Alignment Table</h3>
  <p class="section-intro" style="margin-bottom:12px;">Read across each row to see how all six skill areas work together within the same unit.</p>
  <div class="table-wrap">
  <table class="align-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Unit</th><th>Vocabulary</th><th>Grammar & Verb Patterns</th><th>Connectors</th><th>Pronunciation & Writing</th><th>Context & Culture</th><th>Communication Strategies</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>U1: Hello, I'm Me</strong><br><em>Identity & First Contact</em></td>
      <td>Greetings & farewells. Basic social interaction. Personal space vocabulary. Basic professions (estudiante, profesor/a, doctor/a, mesero/a) for <em>¿A qué te dedicas?</em></td>
      <td>SER (soy/es/eres — multiple forms, one verb system). Tú/usted as a social choice, not a grammar topic. <em>Hay</em> as a fixed expression (there is/are — one form, no conjugation). Question formation: ¿Qué? ¿De dónde? ¿Cómo?</td>
      <td>Greeting/farewell formulas as conversation openers. Basic question words as conversation thread: qué, cuál, cómo, de dónde, quién.</td>
      <td>Spanish vowel system (5 pure vowels vs. ~15 in English). The ñ. Inverted punctuation (¿ ¡). Cognate pronunciation: stress on correct syllable.</td>
      <td>Formal vs. informal: tú/usted selection by social context (professor = usted, classmate = tú). Fixed courtesy: Mucho gusto, Con permiso, Gracias.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Mexican greeting practices — beso, abrazo, handshake. The diminutive as warmth (cafecito, ahorita). A first meeting at the feria.</span></td>
      <td>Repair phrases: ¿Cómo? ¿Puede repetir? Más despacio, por favor. ¿Qué significa ___? — memorized chunks that keep conversation going.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>U2: The World Around You</strong><br><em>People, Things, Spaces</em></td>
      <td>Family (mamá, papá, hermano/a, esposo/a, hijo/a). Descriptive adjectives. Basic objects & food at the feria. Basic clothing as description vocabulary: camisa, pantalones, zapatos, vestido.</td>
      <td>Articles (el/la/los/las): gender & number. Descriptive adjectives (agreement). Possessives (mi, tu, su, nuestro). Numbers 0–30. SER + adjective. <em>A personal</em>: learners encounter it naturally in input (Conozco <strong>a</strong> Sofía) before any rule is given.</td>
      <td>Enumeration: y, también, hay. Basic contrast: pero. Interrogatives: ¿Cuántos? ¿Cómo es?</td>
      <td>Spanish alphabet. Writing numbers 0–100. Syllabic rhythm of Spanish vs. stress-timed English (awareness, not mastery).</td>
      <td>Diminutives as affection markers, not size. Physical contact norms in Mexico vs. US.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Don Marcos's puesto at the feria — Hay café de olla, hay tamales, hay agua de jamaica.</span></td>
      <td>Cognate strategy: recognizing English-Spanish cognates as a bridge (universidad, información, hospital).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>U3: Life in Motion</strong><br><em>Actions & Daily Routine</em></td>
      <td>Daily routines: desayunar, caminar, estudiar, trabajar, comer, dormir. School subjects & areas of study.</td>
      <td>Present tense: regular -AR, -ER, -IR verbs (full paradigms). ESTAR (location, conditions, emotions). <em>Querer + infinitive</em> (intention).</td>
      <td>Sequencing: primero, después, luego, entonces, finalmente. Time-of-day markers: por la mañana/tarde/noche. Simple frequency: siempre, a veces, nunca (receptive).</td>
      <td>Stress distinction preview: habló vs. hablo — accent as grammar marker (groundwork for SP102).</td>
      <td>Turn-taking: greet → respond → ask → farewell. How routines differ culturally.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Sofía's daily routine in Puebla — café con don Marcos, class, mercado with Tomás.</span></td>
      <td>Relying on rehearsed formulas: Novice learners depend on practiced complete phrases. The strategy is recognizing which one fits the moment.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>U4: Time, Numbers & Schedule</strong><br><em>Organizing Life</em></td>
      <td>Time expressions (la hora). Numbers 31–100. Schedules & calendar. Weather as everyday chunks: hace calor/frío, llueve, está nublado, hace sol.</td>
      <td>TENER (possession & age) and VENIR. Telling time: Es la una, Son las tres y media. IR (present). Stem-changing verbs (e>ie, o>ue). Irregular yo forms (hago, salgo, pongo).</td>
      <td>Time markers: ahora, en este momento, hoy, esta semana. Questions: ¿A qué hora? ¿Cuándo? ¿Qué día?</td>
      <td>Clock time conventions (12h vs. 24h in Mexico). Stress patterns in number words.</td>
      <td>Time as social structure: Mexican time flexibility. Schedule differences (la comida at 2–3 PM).<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Elena organizing the family's week — work, school, feria, church.</span></td>
      <td>Managing not-knowing: accepting that not understanding everything is normal. "Listen for what I DO understand" instead of freezing.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>U5: Here & Now</strong><br><em>Location, Movement, Plans</em></td>
      <td>Hobbies, sports, entertainment. Emotional/physical states (contento, cansado, nervioso). Places & movement. Food & everyday objects.</td>
      <td>ESTAR (location + emotions). Present progressive (estar + gerundio). Contrast SER vs. ESTAR. Direct objects. <em>Ir a + infinitivo</em> (immediate plans). <em>Estar + gerundio</em> (action in progress).</td>
      <td>Contrast: pero, y. Sequence review: primero → después → luego → finalmente. Frequency: siempre, a veces, nunca.</td>
      <td>Rhythmic phrasing in longer sentences. Cognate pronunciation control. Basic accentuation: recognizing stressed syllable in frequent words (café, está, dónde).</td>
      <td>The invitation as social gesture in Mexico. Silence, distance, and tone carry different cultural meaning than in English.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Sofía and Tomás at Xochimilco — describing what's happening right now.</span></td>
      <td>Listening comprehension: global understanding before detail. "What do I understand?" before "What don't I understand?"</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>CB: Coverage Boost</strong><br><em>Full SP101 Grammar</em></td>
      <td>Recycled contexts from U1–U5 with expanded linguistic tools.</td>
      <td>Stem-changing verbs (full). Irregular yo forms (expanded). SER vs. ESTAR contrast (formal). Direct object pronouns.</td>
      <td>All SP101 connectors in more complex combinations.</td>
      <td>All SP101 pronunciation & writing content recycled in new contexts.</td>
      <td>Register recycling: tú/usted in new, less predictable situations.</td>
      <td>All SP101 strategies recycled with increasing independence.</td>
    </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>

