</section>

<!-- ═══ SP102 ═══ -->
<section id="sp102">
  <div class="level-header sp102">
    <h2>SP102 — Elementary Spanish II</h2>
    <div class="target">ACTFL Target: Intermediate Low</div>
    <div class="desc">Narration, obligation, and experience. Learners tell stories about the past, explain habits, describe people in detail, and sustain longer conversations — creating with the language for the first time.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="se-note">📌 <strong>The word "se" in Spanish</strong> has four distinct uses, and this course introduces them gradually: reflexive & lexical <em>se</em> (Cluster 2), impersonal & passive <em>se</em> (Cluster 3), and reciprocal <em>se</em> (previewed in Cluster 6, formalized in SP201).</div>

  <h3>SP102 — Full Alignment Table</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
  <table class="align-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Cluster</th><th>Vocabulary</th><th>Grammar & Verb Patterns</th><th>Connectors</th><th>Pronunciation & Writing</th><th>Context & Culture</th><th>Communication Strategies</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 1: Shopping & Transactions</strong><br><em>Markets & Money</em></td>
      <td>Shopping: products, prices, markets, bargaining. Numbers 101+. Clothing expanded: llevar, ponerse, quitarse + wardrobe vocabulary.</td>
      <td>Regular preterite (-é, -aste, -ó, -amos, -aron). Indirect object pronouns (me, te, le, nos, les). Demonstrative adjectives (este, ese, aquel).</td>
      <td>Past narrative sequence: primero, luego, después, al final, ese día, la semana pasada.</td>
      <td>Accent rules: agudas, graves, esdrújulas. Preterite pronunciation: habló (past) vs. hablo (present) — the accent mark as grammar signal.</td>
      <td>Price negotiation: ¿Cuánto cuesta?, ¿Me da un descuento?, Es muy caro. Bargaining culture in Mexican markets.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Don Marcos selling at the feria — haggling, rapport, trust.</span></td>
      <td>Circumlocution: <em>Es una cosa que sirve para... / Es un lugar donde... / Es como un/una...</em> — the key survival strategy for this level.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 2: Daily Routines & Habits</strong><br><em>Personal Care & Culture</em></td>
      <td>Personal care (despertarse, bañarse, vestirse). Cultural habits. Professions expanded: ¿A qué se dedica? + traits for different jobs.</td>
      <td>Reflexive verbs (levantarse, acostarse, vestirse). Indefinite & negative words (alguien/nadie, algo/nada).<br><strong>Uses of "se" — Part 1:</strong> Reflexive <em>se</em> (La madre se baña) and lexical <em>se</em> — verbs that simply include <em>se</em> in their dictionary form (olvidarse, darse cuenta, morirse).</td>
      <td>Frequency & negation: siempre, a veces, nunca, nadie, nada, tampoco, ni...ni. Sequence: antes de, después de, al + infinitive.</td>
      <td>Diacritic accent: el/él, tu/tú, si/sí, se/sé. b/v in Mexican Spanish (same sound); c/s/z seseo.</td>
      <td>Expanded register: adjusting tone by relationship. Indirect preference: me gusta más..., prefiero..., no me gusta tanto.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Morning routines across Mexican families — la comida as social ritual, sobremesa.</span></td>
      <td>Lexical approximation: using a close word when the exact one is unknown (lavar for limpiar). Staying in Spanish instead of switching to English.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 3: Food, Celebrations & Experiences</strong><br><em>Social Life</em></td>
      <td>Food, meals, gastronomy. Social meals. Celebrations (cumpleaños, quinceañera, fiestas patrias, Día de Muertos).</td>
      <td>Gustar + faltar, quedar (me falta tiempo, nos quedan dos días). Preterite of SER and IR (fui, fuiste, fue...).<br><strong>Uses of "se" — Part 2:</strong> Impersonal <em>se</em> — no specific subject (se puede, se dice, se habla español). Passive <em>se</em> — the thing receives the action (se venden tamales).</td>
      <td>Comparison: más que, menos que, tan...como, mejor, peor. Expansion: que, lo que — building longer sentences.</td>
      <td>Narrative intonation: continuation vs. closure. Spelling changes in irregular preterites (busqué, llegué, empecé).</td>
      <td>Food as social act (sobremesa). Celebrations as family cohesion. Mexican indirectness: diminutives to soften (un momentito, cerquita, ahorita). Courtesy expressions <em>quisiera, me gustaría</em> used as fixed phrases (the full conditional verb system comes in SP201).<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Quinceañera planning — doña Rosa organizing the celebration.</span></td>
      <td>Paraphrasing: restating ideas to confirm understanding (Entonces, ¿tú dices que...?). Narration management: connectors as crutches (y entonces..., y luego...).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 4: Health & Wellbeing</strong><br><em>Body, Symptoms, Services</em></td>
      <td>Health, symptoms, medical services (me duele, tengo fiebre, la farmacia). Basic body parts.</td>
      <td>Preterite of stem-changing verbs. Double object pronouns (se lo dije). Saber vs. conocer. <em>Tener que + infinitive</em> (obligation); <em>soler + infinitive</em> (habits).</td>
      <td>Contextual framing: antes, mientras, generalmente, de niño/a, en esa época. Spatial reference: este/ese/aquel.</td>
      <td>Speech rhythm: natural phrasing in longer sentences. Discursive pauses in oral narration.</td>
      <td>Medical visit in Mexican context (pharmacy first, cultural self-medication). Register: formal with doctor, informal with friend.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Tomás at the farmacia — navigating health advice without a doctor visit.</span></td>
      <td>Emerging self-correction: noticing and correcting own errors in real time (dijo... no, dije).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 5: Past Narration</strong><br><em>Telling Stories</em></td>
      <td>Biographical vocabulary. Historical events (basic). Narrated experiences & milestones.</td>
      <td>Irregular preterites (tuve, hice, puse, dije, traje). Verbs that change meaning in preterite (saber = find out, conocer = meet).<br><strong>Preterite vs. Imperfect contrast</strong> — the most important grammar structure at this level. Completed actions vs. habitual or background description. Treated as a dedicated structure, like SER/ESTAR was in SP101.</td>
      <td>Narrative frame: mientras + imperfect background, preterite for main events. Temporal anchoring: en esa época, de niño, antes.</td>
      <td>Preterite vs. present stress (habló/hablo) — now productive, not just receptive.</td>
      <td>Narration as social act: telling a personal experience, sharing an anecdote — why storytelling matters in interaction.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Don Felipe narrating his journey to the feria — imperfect for background, preterite for events.</span></td>
      <td>Sustaining a brief story without collapsing. Requesting time: A ver..., Es que..., Bueno, lo que pasó fue que...</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 6: Describing & Comparing</strong><br><em>People, Objects, Experiences</em></td>
      <td>People description (physical + personality). Clothing in narrative context. Comparison vocabulary.</td>
      <td>Comparatives & superlatives. Relative pronouns (que, quien, lo que). Contrast qué/cuál. <em>A personal</em> — now actively produced: Busco <strong>a</strong> mi hermano vs. Busco un libro. Imperfect (hablaba, comía, vivía). Adverbs. Reciprocal <em>se</em> (preview): se saludan, se abrazan.</td>
      <td>Expansion: que, lo que, el/la cual — longer sentences with basic subordination. Descriptive sequencing.</td>
      <td>Full accentuation rules applied. Orthographic preterite changes consolidated.</td>
      <td>Describing people including clothing — ser for identity, estar for state, llevar for clothing.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: The feria's vendors and visitors — a descriptive scene using all SP102 tools.</span></td>
      <td>All SP102 strategies with increasing independence. Circumlocution + approximation as default survival tools.</td>
    </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>

