<!-- ═══ SP201 ═══ -->
<section id="sp201">
  <div class="level-header sp201">
    <h2>SP201 — Elementary Spanish III</h2>
    <div class="target">ACTFL Target: Intermediate Mid/High</div>
    <div class="desc">Subjectivity, future, and hypothesis. Learners express opinions, give commands, react emotionally, debate social issues, and begin exploring hypothetical thinking — using the subjunctive to say what they feel, not just what they know.</div>
  </div>

  <h3>SP201 — Full Alignment Table</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
  <table class="align-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Cluster</th><th>Vocabulary</th><th>Grammar & Verb Patterns</th><th>Connectors</th><th>Pronunciation & Writing</th><th>Context & Culture</th><th>Communication Strategies</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 1: Instructions & Regulation</strong><br><em>Commands & Norms</em></td>
      <td>Technology & digital media. Urban life, services & procedures (bank, mail, transport). Household responsibilities.</td>
      <td>Affirmative & negative tú commands (habla / no hables). Formal commands (usted/ustedes). Por vs. para.<br><strong>Uses of "se" — Part 3:</strong> Reciprocal <em>se</em> — doing something to each other (nos vemos, se escriben, se abrazan). Now explicitly taught.</td>
      <td>Cause & purpose: porque, para que, ya que, dado que. Logical sequence: es decir, en otras palabras.</td>
      <td>Pragmatic intonation: patterns for commands (firm vs. polite), suggestions (rising), opinions (assertive vs. tentative).</td>
      <td>Social regulation: commands vary by relationship (boss, friend, parent, stranger). Register: tú/usted + formal/informal commands together.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Doña Rosa giving instructions for the quinceañera — firm with vendors, warm with family. A narrative that shows how register shifts in real Mexican social contexts.</span></td>
      <td>Strategic discourse planning: mentally organizing before speaking. Crutch markers: pues, a ver, lo que quiero decir es...</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 2: Feelings & Reactions</strong><br><em>Subjectivity & Emotion</em></td>
      <td>Wellbeing, exercise & nutrition. Values, cultural identity & social thought. Opinion vocabulary: creer, opinar, considerar, proponer, sugerir, recomendar — verbs that trigger the subjunctive, learned as functional vocabulary.</td>
      <td>Present subjunctive with verbs of emotion (me alegra que...), doubt (dudo que...) and negation (no creo que...). Subjunctive in adjective clauses (busco un lugar que tenga...). Subjunctive vs. indicative contrast in noun clauses.</td>
      <td>Cause-emotion-result: me alegra que..., es triste que..., me preocupa que... Concession: aunque + indicative/subjunctive; a pesar de que; si bien — acknowledging the opposing view before responding.</td>
      <td>Subjunctive spelling: systematic changes (busque, llegue, empiece; conozca, produzca). Discourse connector pronunciation as fluid phonetic blocks.</td>
      <td>Nuanced opinion: creo que + indicative vs. no creo que + subjunctive — grammar as a tool for expressing stance. Complex courtesy: me gustaría que..., ¿sería posible que...?, ¿te importaría...?<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: A community discussion about a local issue — formal register, emotional reactions, respectful disagreement. Historical context: the tradition of collective decision-making in Mexican communities.</span></td>
      <td>Advanced paraphrasing: es decir, o sea, en otras palabras — for clarifying both your own and your interlocutor's meaning.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 3: Future Plans & Possibilities</strong><br><em>Projection & Hypothesis</em></td>
      <td>Environment, nature & conservation. Social issues (recycling, pollution, protected areas, natural resources).</td>
      <td>Future simple (hablaré, comeré, viviré). Conditional simple (hablaría, comería, viviría). Introduction to imperfect subjunctive in fixed conditional structures: <em>Si tuviera tiempo, viajaría... Si pudiera, lo haría.</em> <em>Debería / sugerir que</em> (recommendation); <em>podría / me gustaría</em> (possibility & courtesy).</td>
      <td>Temporal projection: más adelante, en el futuro, a largo plazo, para entonces. Condition & consequence: si + present → future; si + imperfect subjunctive → conditional (introduction).</td>
      <td>Future & conditional accentuation: agudas (hablaré) and graves (hablaría) — accent as morphological anchor.</td>
      <td>Group plan coordination: ¿nos vemos?, te aviso — social commitment vs. literal commitment in Mexican culture. Indirect style: diminutives + conditional to soften requests.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Planning a community project — negotiating, proposing, projecting consequences.</span></td>
      <td>Written text management: plan → write → review. Editing questions: Is it cohesive? Coherent? Is the register appropriate?</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 4: Experience & Reflection</strong><br><em>Looking Back, Looking Forward</em></td>
      <td>Values, identity, cultural thought. Cross-cultural comparison vocabulary.</td>
      <td>Present perfect (he hablado, has comido, hemos vivido). Nosotros commands (hablemos, comamos). <em>He visto, hemos decidido</em> (accumulated experience); <em>deber + infinitive / haber que</em> (formal regulation).</td>
      <td>Transition markers: sin embargo, por lo tanto, además, a pesar de, no obstante, por un lado... por otro. Argumentative text organization: en primer lugar / en segundo lugar / finalmente; en conclusión / en resumen.</td>
      <td>Formal writing: capitalization, complex punctuation (commas in subordinate clauses, semicolons). Extended oral production: rhythm control, strategic pauses, emphasis.</td>
      <td>Argumentation: evidence + concession (aunque...) + conclusion. Partial disagreement & hedging: Sí, pero... / No sé, pero yo creo que... / Tal vez tengas razón, pero... / Puede ser que... / Lo dudo mucho.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Debating a social issue — balancing directness with Mexican indirectness norms.</span></td>
      <td>Hedging as strategy: memorized formulas for maintaining discussion without confrontation. Active self-correction: conscious monitoring of your own speech.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cluster 5: Opinion & Argument</strong><br><em>Taking a Stance</em></td>
      <td>Abstract social vocabulary: migration, diversity, social justice, education, technology's role.</td>
      <td>Advanced relative pronouns (que, quien, cuyo, el/la cual). Full subjunctive vs. indicative contrast in noun clauses — consolidated.</td>
      <td>Full argumentative structure: thesis → argument → concession → conclusion. All SP201 connectors consolidated.</td>
      <td>All SP201 pronunciation & writing content consolidated. Fluent production of discourse markers as phonetic blocks.</td>
      <td>Channel adaptation: text message vs. formal email vs. oral presentation vs. spontaneous conversation — choosing the right linguistic tools for the medium.<span class="cultural">Cultural anchor: Writing an opinion piece for a community audience — connecting personal cultural experience to broader social argument.</span></td>
      <td>All SP201 strategies consolidated with independence. Writing process management as habitual practice.</td>
    </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>

