<section id="strategies">
  <h2>Academic Literacy — Reading, Writing & Speaking Across Levels</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">How the three core academic skills progress. In SLE: reading strategies live in Cuéntame lessons, writing strategies in micro-performances and unit projects, and oral communication strategies in every lesson's Strategy Coaching.</p>
  <div class="table-wrap">
  <table class="prog-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>SP101 · Novice Mid/High</th><th>SP102 · Intermediate Low</th><th>SP201 · Intermediate Mid/High</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Reading</strong></td><td>Global comprehension with visual support and glosses. Identifying who, what, where in short texts. Recognizing cognates.</td><td>Scanning for specific information. Skimming for central theme. Following narrative sequence in past-tense texts. Inferring meaning from context.</td><td>Argumentative texts: identifying thesis, evidence, and conclusion. Evaluating argument effectiveness. Recognizing how connectors organize a text.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Writing</strong></td><td>Simple present-tense sentences. Organized lists. Filling in templates with personal information. Using y, pero to connect.</td><td>Narrative paragraphs with temporal sequence. Organization: beginning → development → closure. Sequence and contrast connectors. Basic subordination.</td><td>Short argumentative texts: thesis + argument + concession + conclusion. Cause/effect connectors. Editing for cohesion, coherence, and register.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Oral Communication</strong></td><td>Basic turns: greet, respond, ask, farewell. Repair strategies. Relying on rehearsed formulas.</td><td>Sustaining a brief narration. Approximation and circumlocution. Expressing basic agreement and disagreement.</td><td>Partial disagreement with hedging. Organizing oral arguments. Maintaining fluency in extended discourse. Reformulation in real time.</td></tr>
